`Partial<T>` wraps every property of T in `?`, making them all optional:

```typescript
type Partial<T> = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K]; };

interface User { id: number; name: string; email: string; }
type PartialUser = Partial<User>;
// { id?: number; name?: string; email?: string; }
```

Common use cases:
ŌĆó PATCH endpoints: `function updateUser(id: Id, changes: Partial<User>)` ŌĆö only send changed fields
ŌĆó Builder patterns: start empty and set one field at a time
ŌĆó Test factories: provide only the fields you care about

Note: `Partial<T>` is SHALLOW. `{ address: { city: string } }` becomes `{ address?: { city: string } }` ŌĆö `city` is still required if `address` is provided. For deep recursion you need a custom `DeepPartial<T>`.

`Required<T>` is the OPPOSITE of `Partial<T>`. It removes the `?` from every property:

```typescript
type Required<T> = { [K in keyof T]-?: T[K]; };
// The `-?` syntax removes optionality

interface Config {
  host?: string;
  port?: number;
  timeout?: number;
}
type FullConfig = Required<Config>;
// { host: string; port: number; timeout: number; } ŌĆö all required!
```

Use cases:
ŌĆó After a config resolution step that fills in all defaults, express that the fully resolved config has all fields
ŌĆó Converting an incoming partial DTO to a fully populated entity after database fetch
ŌĆó Asserting that all optional fields must be provided in a specific context

Opposites of each other:

`Pick<T, K>` ŌĆö keep ONLY the properties whose keys are in K:
```typescript
type Pick<T, K extends keyof T> = { [P in K]: T[P]; };

type PostPreview = Pick<Post, 'id' | 'title' | 'createdAt'>;
// Only id, title, createdAt ŌĆö perfect for a list view
```

`Omit<T, K>` ŌĆö include EVERYTHING EXCEPT the keys in K:
```typescript
type OmitId<T> = Omit<T, 'id'>;
type CreateUserInput = Omit<User, 'id' | 'createdAt'>;
// Remove auto-generated fields for creation DTOs
```

Note: `Omit` is NOT distributed over union types the same way `Pick` is. If T is a union, `Omit<T, K>` might not give you what you expect ŌĆö prefer a distributive version:
```typescript
type DistributiveOmit<T, K extends keyof any> = T extends any ? Omit<T, K> : never;
```

`Record<K, V>` creates an object type where every key in K maps to a value of type V:

```typescript
type Record<K extends keyof any, T> = { [P in K]: T; };

// Dictionary
type UserMap = Record<string, User>;

// Exhaustive map ŌĆö TypeScript ensures ALL keys are handled
type Locale = 'en' | 'fr' | 'de';
const translations: Record<Locale, string> = {
  en: 'Hello',
  fr: 'Bonjour',
  de: 'Hallo'
  // Forgetting any key ŌåÆ compile error!
};

// Grouping by category
const groupedUsers: Record<string, User[]> = {};
```

Difference from `{ [key: string]: V }`: `Record<Locale, string>` with a union K is EXHAUSTIVE ŌĆö all keys must be present. `{ [key: string]: V }` is an index signature that accepts any string key.

`Parameters<T>` extracts the parameter types of a function as a TUPLE:

```typescript
type Parameters<T extends (...args: any) => any> =
  T extends (...args: infer P) => any ? P : never;

function createUser(name: string, age: number, admin: boolean) { ... }
type CreateUserParams = Parameters<typeof createUser>;
// [name: string, age: number, admin: boolean]

// Pick specific parameter:
type NameParam = Parameters<typeof createUser>[0]; // string
```

Use cases:
ŌĆó Building wrappers/proxies that accept the same args as the original
ŌĆó Spreading params from one function to another
ŌĆó Creating mock functions with the right types in tests

Complement: `ReturnType<T>` for the return type, `ConstructorParameters<T>` for class constructors.

`readonly T[]` or `ReadonlyArray<T>` removes mutating methods from the array type:

```typescript
function sum(numbers: readonly number[]): number {
  // numbers.push(1); // Error! .push doesn't exist on readonly number[]
  return numbers.reduce((a, b) => a + b, 0);
}
```

Why use it for parameters:
ŌĆó DOCUMENTS INTENT: signals the function promises not to mutate the input array (important for functional code)
ŌĆó SAFETY: prevents accidental mutation inside the function
ŌĆó LISKOV: a `readonly number[]` parameter ACCEPTS both `number[]` and `readonly number[]` ŌĆö more flexible than `number[]`

Note: `readonly T[]` is a compile-time contract only ŌĆö the actual array is not frozen at runtime. Use `Object.freeze()` for runtime immutability.
